UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 2452
1 (b) Abstinence from sexual activity is the only certain way to avoid unintended
2 pregnancy, sexually transmitted diseases, and other associated health
3 problems;
4 (c) The best way to avoid sexually transmitted diseases and other associated
5 health problems is to establish a permanent mutually faithful monogamous
6 relationship;
7 (d) A policy to respect parental rights by ensuring that:
8 1. Except as provided in subsection (5)[(4)](b) of this section, children in
9 grade five (5) and below do not receive any instruction through
10 curriculum or programs on human sexuality or sexually transmitted
11 diseases; or
12 2. Any child, regardless of grade level, enrolled in the district does not
13 receive any instruction or presentation that has a goal or purpose of
14 students studying or exploring gender identity, gender expression, or
15 sexual orientation; and
16 (e) A policy to notify a parent in advance and obtain the parent's written consent
17 before the parent's child in grade six (6) or above receives any instruction
18 through curriculum or programs on human sexuality or sexually transmitted
19 diseases authorized in this section.
20 (2) Each school district shall adopt health curriculum for students in grade six (6) or
21 above that includes instruction on human growth and development. The
22 instruction on human growth and development shall include a presentation of:
23 (a) A high-definition ultrasound video, at least three (3) minutes in duration,
24 showing the development of the brain, heart, sex organs, and other vital
25 organs in early fetal development; and
26 (b) An age-appropriate, high-quality, computer-generated rendering or
27 animation showing the process of human cell fertilization and every stage of
Page 2 of 4
XXXX 3/1/2026 10:43 AM Jacketed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 2452
1 human development inside the uterus, noting significant markers in cell
2 growth and organ development for the duration of the pregnancy until
3 birth.
4 (3) Any course, curriculum, or program offered by a public school on the subject of
5 human sexuality or human growth and development provided by school personnel
6 or by third parties authorized by the school shall:
7 (a) Provide an alternative course, curriculum, or program without any penalty to
8 the student's grade or standing for students whose parents have not provided
9 written consent as required in subsection (1)(e) of this section;
10 (b) Be subject to an inspection by parents of participating students that allows
11 parents to review the following materials:
12 1. Curriculum;
13 2. Instructional materials;
14 3. Lesson plans;
15 4. Assessments or tests;
16 5. Surveys or questionnaires;
17 6. Assignments; and
18 7. Instructional activities;
19 (c) Be developmentally appropriate; and
20 (d) Be limited to a curriculum that has been subject to the reasonable review and
21 response by stakeholders in conformity with this subsection and KRS
22 160.345(2).
23 (4)[(3)] A public school offering any course, curriculum, or program on the subject of
24 human sexuality or human growth and development shall provide notification to
25 the parents of a student at least two (2) weeks prior to the student's planned
26 participation in the course, curriculum, or program. The notification shall:
27 (a) Inform the parents of the provisions of subsection (3)[(2)] of this section;
Page 3 of 4
XXXX 3/1/2026 10:43 AM Jacketed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 2452
1 (b) Provide the date the course, curriculum, or program is scheduled to begin;
2 (c) Detail the process for a parent to review the materials outlined in subsection
3 (3)[(2)] of this section;
4 (d) Explain the process for a parent to provide written consent for the student's
5 participation in the course, curriculum, or program; and
6 (e) Provide the contact information for the teacher or instructor of the course,
7 curriculum, or program and a school administrator designated with oversight.
8 (5)[(4)] Nothing in this section shall prohibit school personnel from:
9 (a) Discussing human sexuality, including the sexuality of any historic person,
10 group, or public figure, where the discussion provides necessary context in
11 relation to a topic of instruction from a curriculum approved pursuant to KRS
12 160.345;
13 (b) Providing age-appropriate instruction on child sexual abuse through
14 curriculum or programs in accordance with the standards set forth by the
15 National Children's Alliance and approved by the Children's Advocacy
16 Centers of Kentucky, regardless of grade level; or
17 (c) Responding to a question from a student during class regarding human
18 sexuality as it relates to a topic of instruction from a curriculum approved
19 pursuant to KRS 160.345.
